# piper-control-unit-demo

A modular real-robot control unit for Piper arm, designed to decouple low-level robot control from policy inference, with both real-hardware mode and mock/demo mode.

## Scope
- Connect to a real Piper arm from Ubuntu 20
- Read robot state
- Send joint and gripper actions
- Run actions through a pluggable policy interface
- Support both `real` and `mock` modes

## Non-goals
- No ROS1 inheritance as the main architecture
- No full ROS2 package in v1
- No training pipeline
- No complex GUI as the main control architecture; the optional GUI is only an auxiliary manual tool
- No Cartesian control as the main interface

## Repository layout
- [config/](config/) runtime YAML files
- [docs/](docs/) architecture and bring-up notes
- [src/core/](src/core/) stable control interfaces
- [src/drivers/](src/drivers/) robot and camera drivers
- [src/policies/](src/policies/) mock and remote policy adapters
- [src/app/](src/app/) shared session and manual-control application layer
- [src/gui/](src/gui/) optional PySide6 manual control panel
- [scripts/](scripts/) runnable demos
- [tests/](tests/) mock and safety coverage

## Environment setup
1. Miniconda is installed under `/home/leeviy/miniconda3`.
2. Activate the environment:
   - `source /home/leeviy/miniconda3/etc/profile.d/conda.sh`
   - `conda activate PiperArm`
3. Install dependencies:
   - `pip install -r requirements.txt`

## Mock mode
Run the full loop without hardware:

```bash
source /home/leeviy/miniconda3/etc/profile.d/conda.sh
conda activate PiperArm
cd /home/leeviy/Desktop/PiperArm
python scripts/run_policy_loop.py --mode mock --max-steps 10
```

## Real mode
Real mode now defaults to the official `piper-sdk` `C_PiperInterface_V2` client in [src/drivers/piper_driver.py](src/drivers/piper_driver.py).

Typical flow:

```bash
source /home/leeviy/miniconda3/etc/profile.d/conda.sh
conda activate PiperArm
cd /home/leeviy/Desktop/PiperArm
bash scripts/find_all_can_port.sh
bash scripts/activate_can.sh can0 1000000
bash scripts/check_can.sh can0
python scripts/enable_robot.py --mode real
```

## GUI tool
The Linux GUI is an auxiliary manual-control tool. It uses the shared session layer and still sends all motion through [src/core/executor.py](src/core/executor.py) and [src/core/safety.py](src/core/safety.py); it does not replace the policy/VLA path.

Install GUI dependencies:

```bash
python -m pip install -e ".[gui,real]"
```

Start without hardware:

```bash
bash scripts/launch_gui.sh mock
```

Start with real hardware after CAN is active:

```bash
bash scripts/activate_can.sh can0 1000000 3-1.2:1.0
bash scripts/launch_gui.sh real
```

